@Atlassian - Your policy on bugs says, for Medium:
 - The application or specific feature isn't working as expected, *but there is a workaround available*. Users' experience is impacted, but their job function is not impaired.

Yet, there is no workaround for this. Doesn't that mean this would be categorized as a High?

We don't want to confuse our users about the availability of Assets, so we need to hide every UI element. Assets would be great to integrate, but we have other tooling for configuration management and (government) rules prevent us from getting/using other software.

Gladly we got ScriptRunner and this brings the possibility to hide UI elements. The configuration is a bit rigorous, we want to be sure everything is gone, but if someone has a better suggestion, please let us hear!

Follow the following instructions
 # Add a new Fragment (Gears > ScriptRunner > Fragments > Create Fragment).
 # We use _Hide Assets_ as a {_}Note{_}.
 # Select every element which contains _insight_ or _assets_ in _Hide what_ (you can define multiple).
 # Add the following script to allow only users in the groups _jira-administrators_ and _jira-system-administrators_ to see the Assets UI elements.

{noformat}
import com.atlassian.jira.component.ComponentAccessor

def groupManager = ComponentAccessor.groupManager
def loggedInUser = ComponentAccessor.jiraAuthenticationContext.loggedInUser

final username = loggedInUser.username

def allowedGroups = ["jira-administrators", "jira-system-administrators"].toSet()

if(groupManager.isUserInGroups(loggedInUser, allowedGroups)) {
    true
} else {
    false
}{noformat}
 

This will result in a error message on the board view, this is tracked in JSDSERVER-12124. To resolve this issue, disable the module _rlabs-js-bundle-assets-rebrand-onboarding.js_ of the {_}Assets Plugin{_}.
